18 performance and rate of learning of the pupil over time for the purpose of making
19 data-based decisions concerning the need of the pupil for increasingly intensified
20 services.
21 10. “Specific learning disability” means a disorder in one or more of the basic
22 psychological processes involved in understanding or using spoken or written
23 language which is not primarily the result of a visual, hearing or motor impairment,
24 intellectual disability, serious emotional disturbance, or an environmental, cultural
25 or economic disadvantage. Such a disorder may manifest itself in an imperfect
26 ability to listen, think, speak, read, write, spell or perform mathematical
27 calculations. The term includes, without limitation, perceptual disabilities, brain
28 injury, minimal brain dysfunction, dyslexia and developmental aphasia.
